diff:1670648334:1670100207:=51,69c51%0a%3c #foxbegin 221210-045855-344760#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!Emergent sign languages %0a%3c -> - nathandeyak%0a%3c -> [-09.12.2022 - 20:58-]%0a%3c >>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a%3c (:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a%3c {[foxdelrange button 221210-045855-344760 {$FullName} ]}%0a%3c (:if1end:)%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c It is worth noting that not all sign languages were 'created', rather many simply emerged given the right conditions. One situation is a home of a deaf child, with hearing parents. In this case, a signing system will of necessity arise if an existing one is not learned by the parents, and the child doesn't have access to sign language resources either. Although not usually a complete language, these systems can become very intricate.%0a%3c %0a%3c I have also read of other scenarios, such as schools for the deaf that do not teach a sign language but focus on reading/writing/lipreading, where a sign language naturally emerges among the students outside of the classroom.%0a%3c %0a%3c https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Home_sign#Conditions_for_emergence%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 221210-045855-344760#%0a---%0a> %0a
